AVIAN INFLUENZA (69): INDONESIA, POULTRY, HPAI H5N1
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sun 31 Jul 2016
Source: The Jakarta Post [edited]
http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2016/07/31/bird-flu-rates-rise-again-in-indonesia.html


Indonesia has detected a sharp rise in bird flu cases in July [2016] since the country's last report of an unexpected climb earlier this year, bringing the total number of the cases so far in 2016 to 188.

"The number of bird flu cases has risen in 7 consecutive months since January 2016, with the highest number of cases recorded in April 2016, which is quite alarming. It subsequently fell from May to June 2016, only to rise again this month [July 2016]," Agriculture Ministry official Muhammad Azhar said on Friday [29 Jul 2016].

He made the comments when explaining the results of the government's monitoring of bird flu trends in 2016 to the audience at a poultry health and production seminar in Jakarta.

Azhar said as many as 92 014 poultry had died as a result of the bird flu virus in the last 7 months. Most of them were ducks and layer poultry, which made up almost 60 percent of the total number. The remainder were quails, free-range village chickens and broilers, he added.

Data show that the 3 provinces with the highest number of [outbreaks] are West Java with 65 in total, Lampung with 28 and South Sulawesi with 23 [outbreaks].

Azhar said the highest number of poultry deaths nationwide was recorded in March 2016 with 48 066 deaths, followed by 15 581 in February 2016.

The following months saw vast improvements, with the number of poultry deaths declining to 9860 in April and to 558 in June 2016. However, the rates rose by more than tenfold in July 2016, with 6550 cases recorded, Azhar said.

Azhar noted that the rainy season, which occurred throughout the 1st few months of the year, might have contributed to the deaths of the birds, which might have been vulnerable given poor farm conditions and sanitation.

He further said that monitoring by the ministry's officials had revealed that many farms failed to implement biosecurity measures, a framework in quality maintenance of farm and poultry products developed in collaboration with the United Nation's Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) more than a decade ago, after the virus was 1st detected in Indonesia.

[Byline: Liza Yosephine]

